### Notes on the design

- **True sliding window.** Each request stores its own timestamp. On every call, all timestamps `<= now - windowMs` are evicted, then the remaining count is compared to `maxRequests`. There is no shared interval boundary, so a burst at the end of one minute plus a burst at the start of the next can't slip past — the window always covers the trailing `windowMs` from *now*.
- **`>=` check then push.** The limit is checked *before* recording, so exactly `maxRequests` requests are allowed within any window; the next one is rejected.
- **`X-RateLimit-Reset` / `Retry-After`** are computed from the oldest in-window timestamp (`oldest + windowMs`) — the precise moment a slot frees up — not a fixed clock tick. `Retry-After` is floored at 1 second.
- **Memory management.** The `setInterval` sweep deletes any client whose most recent request is outside the window. `cleanupTimer.unref()` plus the returned `close()` method ensure the timer never keeps the process alive.
- **Single-process only.** State lives in an in-memory `Map`, so this works per Node process. Across a cluster or multiple instances, back it with a shared store (e.g. Redis sorted sets, which model the same sliding window with `ZREMRANGEBYSCORE` + `ZCARD`).

