## How the algorithm works

### The core sliding window loop

```
 time ──────────────────────────────────────────────────────────────►
         │◄──────── windowMs ────────────►│
         │                               now
  ───────┼────────────────────────────────┼────────
  [t1 t2]│ [t3 t4 t5 t6 t7 t8 ... t99]  │
         │                                │
       cutoff               currentCount = 97 → allow (< 100)
       (evict t1, t2)
```

Every call to `middleware()` executes exactly three O(k) steps — no data structure rebalancing, no hash operations beyond the one `Map` lookup, no timers fired per request.

### Why this beats fixed-window

A fixed window resets its counter at `:00`, `:01`, `:02`, … A client can legally fire 100 requests at `:59.999` and another 100 at `:00.001` — 200 requests in 2 ms. The sliding window makes that impossible: whenever you measure a 60-second slice ending at *any* arbitrary moment, the count never exceeds `maxRequests`.

---

## Design decisions worth noting

| Decision | Rationale |
|---|---|
| **`Map` of `number[]`** | O(1) IP lookup; timestamp arrays in insertion order means eviction is always a cheap prefix splice |
| **`timestamps[0] + windowMs`** for `X-RateLimit-Reset` | Tells the client exactly when *their oldest slot* opens up — more accurate than "now + windowMs" |
| **`retryAfterMs = timestamps[0] + windowMs - now`** on 429 | Same logic: retry precisely when the oldest slot ages out, not a full window from now |
| **`cleanupInterval.unref()`** | Allows `node` to exit naturally even if `close()` is never called (defensive; explicit `close()` is still best practice) |
| **`req.socket.remoteAddress` fallback** | Handles edge cases where `req.ip` is undefined (non-HTTP duplex streams, test harnesses, etc.) |

